âMy prom experience was pretty standard. I was a weirdo in a Hawaiian shirt running around, hyping everybody up. And I think I did a really good job â like, I would want to hang out with me at prom again,â says Lonnie, who describes his comedy as quirky, optimistic and thoughtful.

âIâm an optimist so I look at a lot of things like, âHow can we have the most fun with this? How can we make this something that everyone will enjoy and want to be a part of?â I do that with my content, my audience and my community too â I love involving people and bringing everybody together to just have a great time.â

Putting his humor aside, Lonnie recognizes that many proms this year may still look or feel different from proms of years past, but he has advice on keeping a positive outlook. âIf youâre missing out on something, itâs OK to be sad about it. Introducing Vancouver, Canada-based singer/songwriter Jessia (@jessiamusic) and her latest hit âIâm Not Pretty,â a song that started as a form of personal therapy for the musician and has since become a far-reaching anthem for self-acceptance and body positivity.

âI feel like the lyrics have helped me,â says Jessia. âI am the most confident Iâve ever been in my body and I love the person that I look at in the mirror every morning. I don't think I ever felt that way before âIâm Not Pretty.â I also feel like Iâm just the messenger of this song, and this song is so much bigger than just me as an artist.â

In theme with #MentalHealthAwarenessMonth, the message of Jessiaâs song aims to inspire people to let go of the need for validation from others and to love themselves fully and freely.

âAinât nobody got time for social comparisons,â says Jessia. âJust do you and just rock it. Do exactly what you want to do and honestly itâs going to work out so much better than trying to be someone else. Building that relationship with yourself where youâre 100% comfortable with who you are is a really, really beautiful thing.â

âMy freestyle riding represents who I am. It is an extension of my personality and I use it to improvise through the world,â says professional bike athlete Brad Simms (@brad_simms).â£
â£
Brad was introduced to BMX at age 11 by his uncle. âSince then I have been privileged enough to ride my bike in 100+ countries, learn multiple languages, broaden my global perspective and make friends all around the world. I could not have done it without the bike.â£
â£
Freedom of expression is my favorite part about riding BMX. The process of connecting dots that never existed is a feeling that never grows old. You are constantly having to reassess your thinking, because of the mental agility it demands.â£
â£
My technique and trick selection are different at this stage of my career. I search for places to do tricks people think are impossible or unique. Jumping over stuff and riding on walls are my favorite things to do now.â£
â£
The streets are the best for my style of riding as Iâm not confined to one course like I might be in competitions. When I pedal around the city, I donât know who or what I will run into. The unknown is what keeps me going back day after day. The streets are raw, gritty and unforgiving so you have to always be alert.ââ£
â£
Video of @brad_simms by @drewpickles

Darci Adele Shepard-Mobbs (@darciadele) and Mia Knights (@miaxalexis) represent the idyllic nature of their long-term relationship through a magical lens inspired by the Renaissance, 19th century English paintings and the folklore of fairies and elves.â£
â£
âWe like to think the world we have created to be shown by these photos is one of complete content, happiness and calm, since thatâs how we feel around one another,â explain the 18-year-olds who live in Norfolk, England.â£
â£
âWe want to convey to people that itâs OK to wish for things, and that nobody should ever tell you that you canât have something. We both used to believe that we would never be able to find the kind of love we now share, and that we werenât even allowed to want it.â£
â£
We want to inspire the people that see the fairy tale life we live in to believe that itâs not just a wish, and that we are real people with insecurities and imperfections who worked as individuals to believe that we are worthy of love, as is everyone in the LGBTQ+ community if they want it.â£
â£
The best thing about being together is the knowledge that whatever we experience as individuals in life, good or bad, exciting or scary, we are going to have a best friend there to experience it at the same time.ââ£
â£
Photo by @darciadele and @miaxalexis

âIt was the hardest decision for me thus far in my career,â says Tasha. âBut I understood that this moment in time was much bigger than myself and my career. Iâve been given this God-given platform to be a voice for the voiceless. If I didnât use my voice, Iâd be doing a disservice to a lot of people that look like me. I wanted to be on the frontlines; not only in spaces that hard dialogues and decisions were being made, but in the community, at marches and at protests.â

Heading into the new season, Tasha is confident her work as an activist and athlete will be championed by her league both on and off the court. âThe WNBA is constantly pushing boundaries and progressing the needle forward. We are consistently at the forefront of every social issue.â
